Vignette 3: Create URL

Introduction

In the previous vignettes, you will have created your customised BIO-WELL survey and linked this to your Dropbox account for remote storage of participantsâ€™ responses.

In this vignette, we will be deploying the survey onto the Posit Shiny Server and creating a URL to share with participants that provides access to the BIO-WELL survey.

What is the Posit Shiny Server?

The BIOWELL package creates your custom BIO-WELL survey as a Shiny App. Posit Connect is a platform that can be used to publish and share Shiny Apps.

For BIO-WELL survey deployment, we will be using the cloud hosting option for Shiny Apps.

Registering for an account is free. A free account allows users to deploy up to five surveys at one time, and use up to 25 active hours per month. If more active hours are needed, there are paid upgrade options available here.

  • Free - 25 active hours ($0/month*)

  • Starter - 100 active hours ($13/month*)

  • Basic - 500 active hours ($49/month*)

  • Standard - 2,000 active hours ($119/month*)

  • Professional - 10,000 active hours($349/month*)

*Prices correct as of 20/06/2023

Active time is only counted whilst a participant is actively responding to the questions. For example, if your survey takes five minutes to complete, then 300 participants can respond to the survey each month.

Preparation for this stage

Please ensure that you have followed the prior stages outlined in Vignette 1 and Vignette 2. You should now have a folder for your BIO-WELL survey that contains:

  1. .secrets folder containing your activated Dropbox access token named dropbox_token.rds)

  2. Your custom BIOWELL::build_survey() input saved within an R script named app.R. Ensure there is no code other than this function, and that you have called the function using the double colon operator (not library(BIOWELL))

If this is not the case, please revisit the previous vignettes before running create_URL().

Your final BIO-WELL survey Shiny App folder

Step 1: Shiny Server account

The first step is to register for a Shiny Server account via their website.

Creating Shiny Server account

Step 2: Connect your account to R

Shiny Server interacts with R through the package rsconnect. Install rsconnect and load the package library.

# install.packages("rsconnect")
library(rsconnect)
library(BIOWELL)

On the website, click on your profile photo in the top right, and choose Tokens from the drop-down list. Then click to show your accountâ€™s token and secret code. Do not share your accountâ€™s secret with anyone else.

Finding Shiny Server token

This will provide code for you to run in R to connect your Shiny Server account.

rsconnect::setAccountInfo(name = 'biowell-app-testing', # Your Shiny Server account username
                          token = 'string of letters and numbers', # Input your Shiny Server token number here
                          secret = 'string of letters and numbers') # Input your Shiny Server token secret here

Revealing Shiny Server secret

Step 3: Create survey URL

Now, use the BIOWELL package function create_URL() to deploy the app and retrieve a URL for sharing the survey with participants.

path_to_folder <- tempdir() # Replace with path to a local folder. 

appName <- "my_app_name" # Replace with name for your app. 

dir.create(paste0(path_to_folder,"/",appName)) 

create_URL(
  BW_app_path = paste0(path_to_folder,"/",appName),
  BW_app_name = "my_app_name",
  Shiny_Server_user = 'biowell-app-testing'
)

Be patient as this function will take a couple of minutes to deploy your survey on the Shiny Servers. Once completed, your browser window will open on your surveyâ€™s URL, and the URL will be printed in R.

The link is now live and can be shared with participants!

Note: You can monitor your survey on the Posit Shiny Server dashboard.
